The tomb is dated to the late {{ill|7th century|ja|7世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/7th century|qq=}} and belongs to the {{ill|End of the Kofun period|ja|古墳時代終末期|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/End of the Kofun period|qq=}}. The use of {{ill|Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|13=User:Immanuelle/Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=}} is rare outside the Kinai region, but the Bigo area (modern Fukuyama) is notable for adopting this feature in tombs such as the {{ill|Inoko Kofun|ja|猪ノ子古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inoko Kofun|qq=}} and the {{ill|Soneda Shiratsuka Kofun|ja|曽根田白塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Soneda Shiratsuka Kofun|qq=}}. The unique characteristics of Oichi No. 1 Kofun, including its octagonal type and cross-shaped stone chamber, suggest a strong connection to the Kinai-based {{ill|Yamato Kingdom|ja|ヤマト王権|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Kingdom|qq=}}.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref>

