'''Oichi No. 1 Kofun''' (尾市1号墳) is a {{ill|Kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun|qq=}} located in {{ill|Shin'ichi Town|ja|新市町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shin'ichi Town|qq=}}, {{ill|Fukuyama|ja|福山市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukuyama|qq=}}, {{ill|Hiroshima Prefecture|ja|広島県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiroshima Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. It is an {{ill|Octagonal Kofun|ja|八角墳|1=Octagonal Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Octagonal Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Octagonal Kofun|qq=}} and a part of the Oichi Kofun Cluster. The tumulus is not Historic Site1 as a Historic Site.

== Overview ==

Situated in eastern Hiroshima, the tomb is located on the ridge of a hill at the uppermost part of the Ashiuradani Valley, which branches off from the Kamitani River, a tributary of the Ashida River.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref> Excavations were conducted in {{ill|1984|ja|昭和59th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1984|qq=}} and during the years 2002–2007.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref>

The tomb has an octagonal type, measuring approximately 10.5 meters in diameter and 1.95 meters in height. A ring of stones, interpreted as an outer protective stone circle, surrounds the mound.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref> The burial facility is a {{ill|Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|13=User:Immanuelle/Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=}} with a cross-shaped floor plan, opening to the southwest. The layout, featuring three compartments typeing a cross, is unique in Japan.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref> Most burial burial goods have been lost, with only fragments of iron tools and {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sue pottery|13=User:Immanuelle/Sue pottery|qq=}} recovered during excavations.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref>

The tomb is dated to the late {{ill|7th century|ja|7世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/7th century|qq=}} and belongs to the {{ill|End of the Kofun period|ja|古墳時代終末期|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/End of the Kofun period|qq=}}. The use of {{ill|Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|13=User:Immanuelle/Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=}} is rare outside the Kinai region, but the Bigo area (modern Fukuyama) is notable for adopting this feature in tombs such as the {{ill|Inoko Kofun|ja|猪ノ子古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inoko Kofun|qq=}} and the {{ill|Soneda Shiratsuka Kofun|ja|曽根田白塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Soneda Shiratsuka Kofun|qq=}}. The unique characteristics of Oichi No. 1 Kofun, including its octagonal type and cross-shaped stone chamber, suggest a strong connection to the Kinai-based {{ill|Yamato Kingdom|ja|ヤマト王権|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Kingdom|qq=}}.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref>

== Excavation History ==

* '''1984:''' Excavation for preservation purposes (Shin'ichi Town Board of Education, summary report published in 1985).
* '''2002–2007:''' Excavation by Fukuyama City Board of Education, report published in 2008.

== burial ==

[[File:Oichi Kofun, 3D-B2-2.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Overhead view of the stone chamber]]
[[File:Oichi Kofun, 3D-N-2.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Expanded view of the stone chamber]]

The burial facility consists of a {{ill|Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|13=User:Immanuelle/Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=}} with the following area:<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref>
* '''Total chamber length:''' Main axis 6.68 meters; East-West 4.6 meters
* '''Central chamber:''' Length 1.61–1.68 meters, rear wall width 1.16 meters, height 1.15 meters<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Kofun Encyclopedia)|1989}}</ref>
* '''Western chamber:''' Length 1.71–1.75 meters, rear wall width 0.95 meters, height 1.06 meters<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Kofun Encyclopedia)|1989}}</ref>
* '''Eastern chamber:''' Length 1.71–1.79 meters, rear wall width 1.01 meters, height 1.12 meters<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Kofun Encyclopedia)|1989}}</ref>
* '''Passage (Sen-dō):''' Length 4.06 meters

The chambers were constructed using cut granite, with each wall, ceiling, and floor made from a single stone slab.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref> The interior was entirely coated with plaster, with particular attention given to sealing joints between stones.<ref>{{Harvid|Oichi Kofun (Heibonsha, Later Edition)|2006}}</ref>

Unusually, the tomb was built to accommodate three burials, a deviation from the standard single-interment practice of {{ill|Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|ja|横口式石槨|1=Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave Tomb-style Sekkaku|13=User:Immanuelle/Side-entrance Sarcophagus Chamber|qq=}}.<ref>{{Harvid|Shiraishi Taichirō|2007}}</ref>

